<br>
The guards were unaware of what hellish demons lay awake, what horde of corruption rested in the shadows. HE was upon them. The plague, the reaper, the unholy champion of Innoruuk. HE was the Harvester of Souls and HE had come to seek his prizes. <br>
<br>
Like a chill the Harvester crawled into the safety of Storm Keep, detected only by the shivers that were passed off as drafts. Deep into Strom Keep HE went. Searching. Looking. HE had touched the ones HE seeked before. A matter of time til the madness sets in forever. From Pure to Soiled to Unholy Pure they will be. <br>
<br>
In the lowest reaches of Storm Keep, the Harvester found one of his prizes. He layed there, slowly breathing, his fists white knuckeled from the strain. His jaw was clenched in a deathlock, a stern look of discontent upon his brow. Setis layed there, sleeping, but what haunted him while he was awake had followed him into his slumber. <br>
<br>
The Harvester approached the sleeping man, its ever shifting form enveloping the cell. <br>
<br>
The Harvester spoke in a low painful moan, &gt;&gt;sseettiiss&gt;sseettiiss...hhhaaattteee...pppoowwweeerrr..ssseettiisss....hhhaaattteee&gt;pppoowweerr wwwee ggiivvee ssseettiisss, ppoowweerrr wwee ggiivvee&gt;ssseettiiisss&lt;&lt;&quot; the Harvester wailed repeatedly. <br>
<br>
Setis slumped to the floor, a broken man, his training and strength had left him. The Harvester approached the figure, enveloping him in its inky darkness, surrounding him. Setis closed his eyes and prayed for a quick and merciful death, anything than to be the plaything to this demonspawn of Innoruuk. <br>
<br>
Setis cracked his eyes and peered at himself. Was he going mad! He was slowing evaporating! Thoughts raced through his mind faster than a spirited druid. Merciful Gods, I'm being disintegrated! Frantically Setis tried to free himself from the wraithlike prison of the Harvester. Try as he might, Setis was trapped. Head hung low, Setis accepted his fate like a man, a soldier, a leader.<br>
<br>
The last thing he saw was the image of a giant hand as he lost control of his mind. <br>
<br>
Scrambling to his feet Setis looked about his surroundings. Where on Norrath was he? His head ached and his body was sore, but he was free. Free from the damnable cell. Out of the corner of Setis's eye he saw a flash of movement. Quickly he turned to face his guest. The Harvester stood before him again, but this time Setis did not shrink away. <br>
The Harvester floated towards Setis, disfigured limbs flailing blindly, its grotesque maw open in a silent scream. Suddenly, Setis laughed. Not a laugh of merriment or joy, but a sinister laugh. &quot;The Harvester is right!&quot; Setis thought, &quot;It speaks to me!&quot; Setis listened to the mute spectre's telepathic words, his mind dissolving the abominations commands. An evil sneer spread across Setis's chisled features, distorting them. <br>
<br>
With one last motion the Harvester of Souls disappeared, vanishing from sight. Setis turned to journey to his final destination, but found himself being watched by a familiar face. <br>
<br>
&quot;What do we have here! A spy!&quot; Setis exclaimed, a evil smile on his face. <br>
<br>
&quot;Greetings Setis&quot;, the dark elf female said,&quot; I've waited for this day to come.&quot; <br>
<br>
Setis reached over and grabbed Nallae by the arms and drew her close. He breathed her in. Ah, she smelled of battle, of a fresh kill, of a fighter. The scent drove Setis insane, he felt a thirst that could not be quenched. <br>
Setis gazed hard into Nallae's eyes, the coldness reflecting off of his. <br>
&quot;Let us be gone of this place, to one more . . . comfortable&quot;, he said flatly as he led her from the clearing and into the darkening night. <br>
