<br>
“Muffins, muffins,” he grumbled to the spider. <br>
“Muffins everywhere. Muffins coming to get me.”<br>
<br>
He glared at the spider, expecting a response.<br>
“Ahh!,” he screamed, “You’re a muffin too!.”<br>
<br>
Lao ran about the room whipping his arms around without thought. He picked up at chair and threw it into the corner with the silent spider. The chair broke with a crash, missing the spider easily, which quickly retreated out of sight.<br>
<br>
“MUFFINS!” Laocoon yelled at the top of his lungs. “MUFFINS!” <br>
<br>
Outside his door there was a commotion. “Sir, are you alright?”<br>
<br>
Laocoon ran into the door, using his head as a battering ram. “Muffins!” he chanted as his head thudded against the reinforced oak door.<br>
<br>
The guards mumbled to each other, discussing whether they should let him pass out or stop him before he severely hurts himself.<br>
<br>
“When he passes out, he will be safe. We leave it at that,” a guard suggested. <br>
<br>
Laocoon continued to beat upon the door, ranting and screaming. <br>
<br>
“&gt;&gt;mmmaaalllkkkkaaaavvvv&lt;&lt;” a voice moaned.<br>
<br>
Laocoon stopped his assault on the door and turned to face the voice. He stood there, an expressionless look on his face. His pupils were dilated to pinpoints, and drool started to leak from his open mouth as he slowly made a gurgling sound. <br>
<br>
With one warped hand, The Harvester reached into Laocoon’s head and invaded his mind feeding him images, thoughts, and commands. <br>
<br>
Laocoon stood at the entrance to Halas, the cold wind biting at his tanned skin. He paid it no mind, he had a cloak. <br>
<br>
“Warm,” he said like a child as he pulled the cloak around his bare shoulders. <br>
<br>
Laocoon stepped through the gates to Halas and marveled at what he saw. Halas had been violated. A group of children ran along playing. The children, horrible disfigured and scarred, were bouncing the head of a dog in the street, laugh and joking. The trees bore no leaves or needles, they were bare, except for the countless boils that bulges with a sickly unknown fluid. The walls and streets writhed, alive with floundering human parts and gasping human faces. Corpses laid in the streets, some rotting and crawling with maggots, others freshly deposited. Laocoon ripped off an arm of a nearby cadaver and tossed it to the group of children. Amused, they began using the arm as a stick and batted the bloodied head around. With every step Laocoon took inside Halas, the world he saw shifted. What was once there, would be gone in an instant, only to appear again in a slightly different location. <br>
<br>
A faceless little girl approached Laocoon, a gift in her 3 fingered hand, offering it to Laocoon. He stared in amazement at the object. It was a cookie, decorated to resemble Laocoon. He reached out for the cookie, but the girl vanished from his sight. <br>
<br>
Laocoon laughed, totally delirious. <br>
He liked games now. <br>
He liked these fun games. <br>
<br>
“Seek out the muffins I must. Never forget the muffins!” he yelled at the misshapen villagers of Halas. <br>
<br>
Quickly, he retreated from the town, cursing muffins as he went.<br>
